  "solution": {
    "approach": "Observe that for any integer x, choosing a = 0 and b = x satisfies (a & b) + (a | b) = 0 + x = x because 0 & x = 0 and 0 | x = x. Hence the problem reduces to printing \"0 x\" for each test case. This solution works for all allowed values of x and runs in O(T) time.",
    "timeComplexity": "O(T) overall, O(1) per test case.",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(1) extra space besides input and output buffers.",
    "code": {
      "C": "",
      "C++": "",
      "Java": "import java.io.*;\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\n        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));\n        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();\n        int T = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());\n        for (int i = 0; i < T; i++) {\n            String line;\n            while ((line = br.readLine()) != null && line.isEmpty()) {}\n            long x = Long.parseLong(line.trim());\n            sb.append(0).append(' ').append(x);\n            if (i + 1 < T) sb.append('\\n');\n        }\n        System.out.print(sb.toString());\n    }\n}",
      "Python3": "",
      "JavaScript": ""
    }
  },
